\ns{ESA Statistics}
\bi
\item U.S. computer and video game software sales generated \$10.5
  billion in 2009.
\item Sixty-seven percent of American households play computer or
  video games.
\item The average game player is 34 years old and has been playing
  games for 12 years.
\item The average age of the most frequent game purchaser is 40 years
  old.  \ei
\end{frame}
\ns{ESA Statistics}
\bi
\item Forty percent of all game players are women. In fact, women over
  the age of 18 represent a significantly greater portion of the
  game-playing population (33 percent) than boys age 17 or younger (20
  percent).
\item In 2010, 26 percent of Americans over the age of 50 play video games, an increase from nine percent in 1999.
\ei
\end{frame}
\ns{ESA Statistics}
\bi
\item Forty-two percent of heads of households play games on a wireless device, such as a cell phone or PDA, up from 20 percent in 2002. 
\item Eighty-two percent of all games sold in 2009 were rated "E" for Everyone, "T" for Teen, or "E10+" for Everyone 10+.  For more information on game ratings, please see www.esrb.org. 
\ei
\end{frame}
\ns{ESA Statistics}
\bi
\item Parents who have children under 18 with a gaming console in the home are present when games are purchased or rented 93 percent of the time.
\item Sixty-four percent of parents believe games are a positive part of their children’s lives.
\ei

\end{frame}
\ns{Journal of Personality and \\Social Psychology, 2000}

\bi
\item
Real-life violent video game play was positively related to aggressive behavior and delinquency
\item
 Academic achievement was negatively related to overall amount of time spent playing video games
\item
Exposure to violent video games will increase aggressive behavior in both the short term (e.g., laboratory aggression) and the long term (e.g., delinquency). 
\ei

\end{frame}
\ns{Psychological Science, 2001}
\bi
\item  Violent video games increase aggressive behavior in children and young adults
\item
Exposure to violent video games increases physiological arousal and aggression-related thoughts and feelings
\item
Playing violent video games also decreases prosocial behavior. 
\ei

\end{frame}
\ns{Journal of Adolescence, 2004}
\bi
\item Exposure to violent video games is significantly linked to increases in aggressive behaviour, aggressive cognition, aggressive affect, and cardiovascular arousal, and to decreases in helping behaviour
\item
 Experimental studies reveal this linkage to be causal
\item
 Previous meta-analytic studies of violent video games underestimate the true magnitude of observed deleterious effects on behaviour, cognition, and affect.
\ei

\end{frame}
\ns{Journal of Adolescence, 2004}

\bi
\item One hundred fifty fourth and fifth graders completed measures of real-life violence exposure, media violence exposure, empathy, and attitudes towards violence. 
\item
Both video game and movie violence exposure were associated with stronger proviolence attitudes.
\item
Regression analyses indicated that only exposure to video game violence was associated with (lower) empathy. 
\ei

\end{frame}
\ns{2005: California bans violent games for minors\\
2011: Supreme Court overrules}
\bi
\item Scalia cites Hansel and Gretel, Cinderella, and Snow White:
 ``Certainly the books we give children to read---or read to them
  when they are younger---contain no shortage of gore.''
\item Thomas dissents: ``freedom of speech ... does not include a
  right to speak to minors ... without going through the minors'
  parents or guardians.''  
\ei
\pspic{10,3}
\grph{1,0}{0.35}{Antonin_Scalia,_SCOTUS_photo_portrait.eps}
\grph{8,0}{0.2}{Justice-Thomas-2.eps}
\epspic

\end{frame}
